    SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT OR BSD-3-Clause OR GPL-2.0-or-later

  * the MIT License            (see LICENSES/MIT.txt),
  * the BSD 3-Clause License   (see LICENSES/BSD-3-Clause.txt), or
  * the GNU General Public License, version 2 or (at your option) any
    later version (see LICENSES/GPL-2.0.txt).

This disjunctive ("OR") choice is deliberate: it lets the material be
reused in MIT-, BSD-, and GPL-style projects alike, including merging
pieces upstream into the Linux kernel and the Linux Test Project (both
GPL-2.0), without anyone having to ask.

Per-file overrides
------------------

If an individual file carries its own SPDX-License-Identifier or license
notice in its header, that notice governs THAT file and takes precedence
over the blanket grant above.  (At the time of writing, no tracked file
does; the whole repository is offered under the choice above.)

Build-time third-party dependencies (not redistributed here)
------------------------------------------------------------

Some sources are *built against* external code that is fetched or
generated at compile time and is NOT included in this repository, e.g.:

  * the kernel nolibc headers (Linux tree, tools/include/nolibc/),
  * a musl/Bootlin cross sysroot and copied kernel UAPI headers
    (kept under userspace/sysroot/, which is .gitignored), and
  * the Linux Test Project (LTP), which the matrix scripts *invoke*.

Those carry their own upstream licenses (typically GPL-2.0,
"GPL-2.0 WITH Linux-syscall-note", LGPL-2.1, or BSD).  Using this
repository's original sources with them at build time does not change
the license of the sources here, but the resulting binaries are of
course subject to the terms of everything linked into them.

